Selecting Climate, Weather, and Soils variables

These variables will serve as predictors in models of vegetation functional composition

Alice Stears

2025-02-25

Background

The weather and climate variables used in this analysis are calculated from DayMet. Information about vegetation functional composition from FIA, AIM, and the LANDFIRE reference database is averaged to the same spatial scale as dayMet, so the dataset we use contains climate and weather information for every dayMet cell that has vegetation functional composition information in each year when that vegetation data were collected.

For each dayMet grid cell in each year when vegetation data was collected, we calculated the following set of climate variables (average values over the previous years (as few as 5 and as many as 30 years)) and weather variable anomalies (the average of values over the previous 3 years relative to the climate average). Note that the we indicate the method of summarizing a climate variable across the climate or weather anomaly years, as well as the units and the method that the recent weather anomaly relative to the climate variable was calculated.

Identify un-correlated climate and soils predictors uniquely for each ecoregion

First, we want to identify a set of possible climate and soils predictors that are not correlated to then use as predictors in models that estimate vegetation composition.

We do this independently for each of two ecoregions (shrub/grassland and forest)

Shrubland and Grassland

First, get data just for grassland/shrubland sites (and drop NAs )

## drop observations so we don't have any NAs
datGrassShrub<- dat %>% 
  select(tmin_meanAnnAvg_CLIM:durationFrostFreeDays_meanAnnAvg_CLIM, swe_meanAnn_5yrAnom:durationFrostFreeDays_meanAnnAvg_5yrAnom, 
         soilDepth:totalAvailableWaterHoldingCapacity, newRegion) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  filter(newRegion == "dryShrubGrass")

The following variables were removed due to correlation with other variables:

  • prcp and prcp_wettestMonth: cor = .955; chose prcp_wettestMonth
  • 95th percentile of annual water deficit and annual water deficit: cor = .97; chose annual water deficit
  • annual water deficit and VPD_mean: cor = .73; chose VPD_mean
  • VPD_mean and tmean: cor = .999; chose tmean
  • tmean and VPD_max: cor = .884; chose VPD_max
  • VPD_max and VPD_max_95: cor = .95; chose VPD_max_95
  • 5th percentile of frost free days and tmin: cor = .97; chose tmin
  • 5th percentile of annual wet degree days and annual wet degree days: cor = .93; chose annual wet degree days
  • tmin and tmean: cor = .92; chose tmean
  • tmax and frost free days: cor = .90; chose frost free days
  • frost free days and above freezing month: cor = .99; chose above freezing month
  • above freezing month and temp of warmest month: cor = .80; chose temp of warmest month
  • % clay and % sand: cor = .79; chose % sand
  • total available water holding capacity and soil depth: cor = .89; chose total available water holding capacity

Forests

First, get data just for forest sites (and drop NAs )

## drop observations so we don't have any NAs
datForest<- dat %>% 
  select(tmin_meanAnnAvg_CLIM:durationFrostFreeDays_meanAnnAvg_CLIM, swe_meanAnn_5yrAnom:durationFrostFreeDays_meanAnnAvg_5yrAnom, 
         soilDepth:totalAvailableWaterHoldingCapacity, newRegion) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  filter(newRegion %in% c("eastForest", "westForest"))

The following variables were removed due to correlation with other variables:

  • tmin and frost free days- 5th percentile: cor = .95; chose frost free days - 5th percentile
  • frost free days - 5th percentile and frost free days: cor = .97; chose frost free days
  • frost free days and above freezing month: cor = .99; chose above freezing month
  • abvFreezingMonth and tmax: cor = .86; chose tmax
  • annWatDef_95 and annWatDef: cor = .98; chose annWatDef

  • annWatDef and prcp_dry: cor = .97; chose prcp_dry
  • prcp_dry and annWetDegDays_5: cor = .93; chose annWetDegDays_5
  • VPD_max and VPD_max_95: cor = .92; chose VPD_max_95
  • VPD_max_95 and VPD_mean: cor = .74; chose VPD_mean
  • VPD_mean and tmean: cor = .99; chose tmean
  • tmean and VPD_min: cor = .80; chose VPD_min
  • totalAvailableWaterHoldingCapacity and soilDepth: cor = .79; chose soilDepth

  • annWetDegDays_5 and prcp_seasonality: cor = .77; chose prcp_seasonality
